==English==
===Etymology===
The name ''Devanagari'' derives from Sanskrit ''[[deva]]'' "divine, excellent", and ''n&#257;gar&#299;'' "urban", a female [[vrddhi]] adjective derived from ''nagara'' "city"; they form a [[tatpurusha]] compound, meaning the "divine urban" script. The '''Nagari''' script is an earlier form of Devanagari, appearing in ca. the [[8th century]] as an eastern variant of the [[Gupta script]], contemporary to [[Sharada]], its western variant. The name Devanagari should therefore be understood as "excellent or perfected form of the Nagari script".
===Adjective===
'''Devanagari''' (Devanāgarī)

#Of the Devanagari script or of a Devanagari alphabet.

===Proper noun===
'''Devanagari'''  ([[देवनागरी]])

#A script used to write several [[Indian]] languages, including [[Sanskrit]], [[Hindi]], [[Marathi]], [[Kashmiri]], [[Sindhi]], [[Bihari]], [[Bhili]], [[Konkani]], and [[Bhojpuri]]. It is also used to write [[Nepali]] in [[Nepal]].

